cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.CE, cs.DS, cs.MA 

The paper proposes a mechanism for learning someone's sense of distinctness between portfolios, which involves Bayesian optimization of a backtested performance metric. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Machine Learning (cs.LG) and Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-categories. The paper also deals with financial asset management, which involves balancing various factors such as risk, exposure, liquidity, and volatility. This suggests that the paper may also belong to the Computational Engineering, Finance, and Science (cs.CE) sub-category. The paper uses numerical experiments to show the impact of personal beliefs in informing the development of a diverse and high-performing portfolio, which suggests that it may also belong to the Data Structures and Algorithms (cs.DS) and Multi-Agent Systems (cs.MA) sub-categories.
